5. Conclusion
The Startup room demonstrates a classic chain of vulnerabilities:

Anonymous FTP write access combined with web-accessible upload directory allows arbitrary file upload and remote code execution.

Unpatched SUID binary (pkexec) leads to trivial privilege escalation.

The main challenge was the absence of a compiler on the target, which was easily bypassed by using a Python-based exploit. This highlights the importance of having alternative exploit methods in your toolkit.

Lessons Learned
Always check FTP for anonymous login and write permissions.

Map web directories to FTP upload folders; they often align.

LinPEAS is invaluable for finding privilege escalation paths quickly.

Python implementations of kernel/SUID exploits are essential when gcc is unavailable.

